Furthermore, the relationship between overall PEC activity and wavelength of the incident light was investigated by the incident photon-to-current conversion efficiency (IPCE) [28]. Fig. S8 shows the IPCE spectra for all samples with water oxidation at 1.23 V vs. RHE, these spectra are integrated and compared with the J-V results in Fig. 4a. The result demonstrates that the onset wavelength (λ
                     open) is around 506 nm for all photoanodes, which is in good agreement with their UV–vis absorption spectra. Additionally, compared with the BV, the OEC decorated photoanodes exhibit an enhanced IPCE over the entire absorption region and the sample of NiCoO2/BV shows the highest activity. The other important consideration in the employment of photoanodes for PEC water splitting is their stability over prolonged illumination [43]. Fig. S9 shows the stability of various samples at 1.23 V vs. RHE in neutral solution, revealing the cocatalysts decorated photoanodes have an obvious stabilization in photocurrent for water oxidation. The results demonstrate the unmodified BiVO4 photoanode only retains ∼60% photocurrent at 60 min compared with the initial value. However, the cocatalysts decorated photoanodes could suppress the photocorrosion and increase the stability of photoanodes (∼93% for NiCoO2/BV at 60 min compared with the tenth minute). In order to identify this photocurrent is only stem from water oxidation (not from the corrosion of material), we checked various elements chemical state of NiCoO2/BV by XPS technique after stability test (Fig. S10). These spectra proved that the binding energy of Bi3+ and V5+ is typically BiVO4 (no V4+ peak around 516.0 eV), also, the peaks of Ni 2p and Co 2p is only contributed by Ni2+ and Co2+ (matched well with before tested sample in Fig. 2). In addition, there is no Ni2+ and Co2+ peaks around 856.4 and 779.6 eV. So, the photocurrent in this system could be considered as the photoanode was only oxidizing water under an extra positive bias for oxygen evolution. Consistently, according to the surface potential, we have provided a successful method to choose an effective OEC NPs, which displays an excellent overall PEC performance (Table 1
                     ).
